```

Now I know `plural("s")` returns `"ses"` (matches `/x$|ch$|s$/i` rule). 

In the mutated code, the misc regex with empty string `\b(?:...|)s\b` - let me think about what this actually matches. The empty alternative makes the group match empty string, so `\b(?:)s\b` = `\bs\b`. This would match the word "s" as a whole word... but "s" gets caught by the `s$` rule first since rules are checked in order (and rules are unshifted, so later-added rules are checked first).

Wait - `rules.unshift` means the LAST added rule is checked FIRST. So the misc regex rule was added after the `s$` rule, meaning the misc regex is checked BEFORE the `s$` rule.

So in mutated code, `plural("s")` - the misc regex `\b(?:...|)s\b` would match "s" (empty + s with word boundaries) → returns "s". But we just saw original returns "ses"...

So in mutated code, `plural("s")` should return `"s"` (matched by misc regex), while original returns `"ses"`.

